<subSubSection id="EB714FB2433A5D3C42237DCA63EA2628" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comments">
<paragraph id="6932AB31397861BBAF7C72B66083CE86" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FE7AEED5C221A3DABE70D020D33C4299" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Otherwise known from British Columbia, Saskatchewan and the western and southern United States, the Virginia male of 
<taxonomicName id="C39E8AA5C3E5198B9FEC7E4BBFEC69B9" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Haplopeodes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplopeodes minutus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutus">
<emphasis id="A894AB2DC2A6871FB72B6B51034A1AE3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Haplopeodes minutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
listed here represents a significant range extension, both for the species and for the genus. The Virginia specimen largely agrees with the western material except the inner lobe of the hypandrium is of a slightly different shape.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="62A28F7DCA4AFD4C2092900DAE40BCB7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This species can be easily confused for 
<taxonomicName id="82961F97C1D3428F55551DCC6009E814" baseAuthorityName="Melander" baseAuthorityYear="1913" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Liriomyza togata" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="togata">
<emphasis id="41E1A11EE1C9DF521136899712992C13" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Liriomyza togata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="42A5A7F6F15CC4CFC305F622EACDD7BF" DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2850.1.1" author="Lonsdale, O" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 123" refId="B138" refString="Lonsdale, O, 2011. The Liriomyza (Agromyzidae: Schizophora: Diptera) of California. Zootaxa 2850: 1 - 123, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2850.1.1" title="The Liriomyza (Agromyzidae: Schizophora: Diptera) of California." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2850.1.1" volume="2850" year="2011">Lonsdale 2011</bibRefCitation>
: figs 225-228) in the west, which is found on 
<taxonomicName id="58811330676ECC13864CB42D0BFB01E2" class="Magnoliatae" family="Umbelliferae" genus="Baccharis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Baccharis douglasii" order="Umbellales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="douglasii">
<emphasis id="32CBD75CA3C0EBE626A20AFC25EC421B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Baccharis douglasii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="DE4F7534FDE25E83CEB439E61F963EDA" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Artemisia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Artemisia douglasiana" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="douglasiana">
<emphasis id="22EE086D64D7B67E3B6BFA887743DF57" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Artemisia douglasiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="38F5B6BF1819A990DFB7DAE82AC09A26" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-94-009-1874-0" author="Spencer, KA" journalOrPublisher="Kluwer Academic Publishers, Dordrecht" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B257" refString="Spencer, KA, 1990. Host specialization in the world Agromyzidae (Diptera). Series Entomologica, 45. Kluwer Academic Publishers, Dordrecht, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/978-94-009-1874-0" title="Host specialization in the world Agromyzidae (Diptera). Series Entomologica, 45." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-94-009-1874-0" year="1990">Spencer 1990</bibRefCitation>
). Like 
<taxonomicName id="FC15AE05A2508D14764F5848E7DB145E" authorityName="Steyskal" authorityYear="1980" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Haplopeodes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplopeodes" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="4E475C5A98760636DD7E5E523B641DBA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Haplopeodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species, this 
<taxonomicName id="816059BFF061BD711622A2490D0D9C1C" authorityName="Mik" authorityYear="1894" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Liriomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0D6BDE0B4918BB93D629A68634B21D8E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Liriomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is sometimes also missing the posterior cross-vein, has a single ors and similar colouration, but the male genitalia are entirely dissimilar. As such, males should be dissected for confident identification.
</paragraph>
